{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/falls-risk-assessment/background-information/risk-factors/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"a2a2cc0e-5dfc-59ed-84a5-c8d26b882acc","slug":"risk-factors","fullItemName":"Risk factors","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field dcc6f47b-381f-4a67-b2d7-20dd3b3f1a91 --><h2>What are the risk factors?</h2><!-- end field dcc6f47b-381f-4a67-b2d7-20dd3b3f1a91 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item accf21f6-768e-4ff6-aa12-a7e25d8925ad --><!-- begin field e7b4e2b6-43ab-4946-8988-6c42bac7e952 --><ul><li><strong>The risk of falling is multifactorial, and prevention is usually based on assessing multiple risk factors </strong>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/falls-risk-assessment/references/\">NICE, 2013a</a>]<strong>.</strong><ul><li>A history of falls is one of the strongest risk factors for a fall, and all older people in regular contact with healthcare professionals should be asked routinely whether they have fallen in the past year.</li><li>Other risk factors for falls in older people include [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/falls-risk-assessment/references/\">Vieira, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/falls-risk-assessment/references/\">PHE, 2017</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/falls-risk-assessment/references/\">Haddad, 2018</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/falls-risk-assessment/references/\">Hopewell, 2018</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/falls-risk-assessment/references/\">PHE, 2018</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/falls-risk-assessment/references/\">BMJ, 2019</a>]:<ul><li>A history of falls — after a first fall, people have a 66% chance of having another fall within a year [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/falls-risk-assessment/references/\">Vieira, 2016</a>].</li><li>Conditions that affects mobility or balance, such as arthritis, diabetes, incontinence, stroke, syncope, or Parkinson's disease.</li><li>Other conditions, including muscle weakness, poor balance, visual impairment, cognitive impairment, depression, and alcohol misuse.</li><li>Polypharmacy, or the use of psychoactive drugs (such as benzodiazepines) or drugs that can cause postural hypotension (such as anti-hypertensive drugs).</li><li>Environmental hazards, such as loose rugs or mats, poor lighting, uneven surfaces, wet surfaces (especially in the bathroom), loose fittings (such as handrails), and poor footwear.</li></ul></li><li>The more risk factors a person has, the greater their risk of falling. <ul><li>Over 65% of people aged 65 years and over have two or more long-term conditions (multimorbidity) [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/falls-risk-assessment/references/\">PHE, 2017</a>]. </li><li>Falls can also be a sign of underlying health issues, such as frailty [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/falls-risk-assessment/references/\">PHE, 2017</a>]. </li></ul></li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field e7b4e2b6-43ab-4946-8988-6c42bac7e952 --><!-- end item accf21f6-768e-4ff6-aa12-a7e25d8925ad -->","topic":{"id":"ec87421f-7ea3-508d-ba78-b50bdd43d3be","topicId":"984467a2-6284-4f25-bee5-6b2b114c7a25","topicName":"Falls - risk assessment","slug":"falls-risk-assessment","lastRevised":"Last revised in January 2019","chapters":[{"id":"f7133733-e8a8-50b4-bc9e-7c7ba69a4c89","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"e0f0a6f6-15c7-5f54-8d83-39498083ebbe","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"d7606aa8-482e-59a5-875e-4ea9e8822ffb","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":